  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Notice how heavily the valuation relies on the discount rate. A lower required return (e.g., 8%) drastically pushes the fair value up.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mortgage Tech Rebound:</strong> If interest rates fall and housing velocity increases, ICE’s mortgage technology segment could experience outsized explosive growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Data Pricing Power:</strong> As algorithmic trading and AI demand more complex datasets, ICE could exert greater pricing power on its proprietary data feeds than we assume.</li>
    <li><strong>Further M&A Synergy:</strong> ICE has a strong track record of acquiring networks and wringing out costs. Future deals could instantly boost FCF beyond our 8% trajectory.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> ICE carries over $20B in debt, largely from the Black Knight acquisition. A structurally higher interest rate environment increases debt servicing costs and reduces available FCF for shareholders.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Scrutiny:</strong> Financial exchanges and data providers face constant global regulatory pressure. Price caps on market data or anti-monopoly interventions could impair growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Prolonged Housing Slump:</strong> If mortgage originations remain depressed for an extended multi-year period, the return on the massive Black Knight investment will be permanently impaired.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 9% discount rate for ICE?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While tech companies often require 10%+, ICE is financial infrastructure with high recurring revenues and wide moats. A 9% discount rate adequately reflects the lower beta and sticky nature of its exchanges and data services compared to consumer discretionary or high-growth software.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why does ICE have negative Net Cash?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">ICE routinely utilizes debt to fund major strategic acquisitions, such as Ellie Mae and Black Knight, which built its mortgage technology monopoly. The massive $20.2B debt load subtracts from the Enterprise Value directly in our calculation.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
